\begin_layout Part*
Quality of Consumption - Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Demand studies in the developing world often work with data that is much
 sparser and has overall less details on the individual households.
 Current surveys mitigate many such issues - but the problems that arise
 out of non-uniform institutions themselves make the standardisation of
 data across the developing countries rather challenging.
 Studies of quality have therefore often limited themselves to food where
 the measurement of quality is independent of consumed brand or type - details
 that are often not recorded in a typical consumer survey.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the current study, we quantify the choice of quality in the developing
 world.
 Instead of focusing on food quality alone, we observe the effect of vast
 differences in life-style that living in urban vs rural areas would bring
 to the consumer in a developing country.
 Further, we comment on how the overall quality may vary with economic inequalit
ies across multiple economies as the consumer spreads the expenditure on
 quality across commodity groups.
 This may provide us a better understanding of how quality of consumption
 changes in response to vast economic changes such as urban developments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To observe the quality of consumption with respect to the income inequalities
 across the developing countries, we motivate a model for substitution between
 a consumer's long-term needs (fulfilled with ownership of assets or improvement
 of income) and the consumer's short-term needs (fulfilled with improved
 quality of consumption).
 It is worth emphasising that we differentiate between quality consumption
 and conspicuous consumption - the latter often implying the exclusive consumpti
on by the rich in a society.
 A comparison of high quality consumption in the different categories of
 a typical demand survey covers the quality concerns for a larger section
 of the population and views status needs of the consumer as part of her
 more general long-term utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We measure the quality in a category (food, energy etc.) using the price
 of the variants in the category simply by classifying high-quality (expensive)
 items apart from their cheaper substitutes.
 The socio-economic standing of the consumer is measured using a vector
 of occupation, education and region/locality/neighborhood.
 The asset ownership and quality consumption both contribute to long-term
 utility and hence status of the consumer.
 This is unlike many studies in consumption - where status is fixed in the
 short-run and the rational consumer, knowing all about her future plans
 is not expected to engage in any status related consumption at all.
 If there is nothing to be gained by conspicuous consumption (i.e.
 Veblen's claim of futility of conspicuous consumption), then there is no
 way for the rational consumer to derive any utility from it.
 The model based on short-term quality advantages and long-term asset ownership
 relates consumption with the perceptions of social mobility.
 We claim that the only advantage status consumption may offer to a rational
 consumer would be through a promise (or a belief) of social mobility.
 The idea itself dates back least as far back as Adam Smith 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SmithMoralSentiments"

\end_inset

 and has been re-evaluated by modern economists in the recent decades 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond,GalbraithAffluent,GalbraithEssential,HirschSocialLimits"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Noticing the separable categories of consumption items, we model the distributio
n of quality and asset ownership amongst the categories.
 If prices are assumed to the stable, the distribution of expensive non-durable
 consumption (ENDC) may change when the individuals acquire assets and spend
 on upkeep/maintenance costs for assets or as they give up on hopes on acquiring
 costlier assets (possibly due to other needs).
 Since consumers don't sacrifice needs for the sake of quality, a rise in
 ENDC must come either from an increase in income or from depletion of savings
 (when needs are fixed).
 Likewise, a drop in ENDC must be due to purchase of assets or a drop in
 income (fixed needs).
 Introducing the price changes, the consumer also considers the price of
 quality in each category.
 Measured with a simple-repackaging model (i.e.
 treating a higher quality item as higher units of the cheaper variant),
 the quality in food may be cheaper than the quality in transport or vice
 versa.
 Faced with a price rise, the choice the consumer faces in cutting down
 quality amongst the categories is driven by her i) habits (myopia) ii)
 non-status needs (number of family members, age etc.) ii) status needs (which
 in-turn depend on the status that the consumer already has - i.e.
 her self-image including the assets owned) and iii) the order of category.
 The consumer is meant to have a pecking order of categories she wants to
 cut down quality on - an order that is determined by how she views her
 status.
 This is the only place where 
