\end_inset

visibility
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of consumption matters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We make two further assumptions in the model.
 First, for simplicity, we assume that every category (food, energy, housing
 etc.) is dominated either by assets or by ENDC (but not both).
 Second, we assume that purchasing assets is always more expensive than
 engaging in ENDC.
 The second assumption gets around the issue that we effectively ignore
 the quality differences in assets when assuming that ENDC dominates in
 a category.
 Empirically, this assumption is not as problematic - since for example
 there are no assets in the food category (or energy) that could matter
 for status while the quality consumption in housing is made irrelevant
 by high (relative) price of housing.
 When quality variation is not observed, only the relevant assets in a category
 matter in the long-term.
 If status needs are fixed over short-term, then the unavailability of the
 quality variation in the category would either increase the savings for
 the next available asset in the category or increase the quality consumption
 in some other category (assuming status needs remain the same).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since status is aggregated from across the commodities, one cannot use the
 two-state budgeting model for status goods 
