\begin_layout Plain Layout
If price sensitivities and total expenditure sensitivities don't follow
 the same channel of communication in the two-state budgeting tree - then
 the necessary condition for two-stage separability is not met (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhilipsAppliedCons,DeatonEconConsumer"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A tree-like model can only be used if we model the discrete choice in 
 the pecking order of quality categories.
 Taking an easier approach with a simple-repackaging model for cross-sectional
 analysis in the current chapter, we consider a quality function 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\theta)$
\end_inset

 so that the cost-function of the category can be written in terms of the
 base-item (the cheapest variant in the category) 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{c}(u,p_{1},p_{2},...,\theta)=c(u,\frac{p_{1}}{h(\theta)},p_{2},...,1)$
\end_inset

 .
 This simply brings the quality-factors on the right hand side of the econometri
c equation 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\beta log(x)+log(h(\theta))+\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 We view quality of significance only in food and energy.
 Housing, for example, doesn't have so much of quality consumption - as
 having a house dominates the effect of quality in the housing category.
 A cross-sectional analysis can tell us what effect having assets may have
 on quality consumption.
 A quantile regression can further explain how quality changes differ in
 the different income quantiles of the society.
 As we have not quantitatively specified the substitution between asset
 and quality in a more explicit model, we refrain from a time-series analysis
 of the asset vs quality substitution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the model doesn't require that a consumer purchase a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

composite item
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of quality (see Deaton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,DeatonSurveyElasticities"

\end_inset

).
 Instead, we believe that quality is a concern for the researcher and not
 for the consumer - who merely exercises her choice given the set of products
 available in the market for given prices (see the clarification from Nelson
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity"

\end_inset

).
 Since status would always be priced in the market, a status item would
 be always more expensive than the rest of the items which provide the same
 functionality (see Chao et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chao1998"

\end_inset

 for substantiation of this argument).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results show that medium assets (TV, cable, appliances) seem limited
 to the cities - and the households in the rural areas miss out on ownership
 of these assets.
 In general, status is more likely to be derived from whatever is available
 as assets in the rural areas - compared to a more advanced economy such
 as that of South Africa.
\end_layout

